## Adoption
<dl class="l-stack-basic">
{% Definition "Permanent Plan" %}
{% Callout %}
DCYF does not provide ongoing supervision.
{% endCallout %}

Post Adoption Services are based upon the child's or youth's needs and family circumstances.

Federal Timeline requires this permanency plan be achieved within 24 months of OPD.
{% endDefinition %}

{% Definition "Objective" %}
Provides permanency for a child or youth when adoption rather than reunification or guardianship is determined to be in their best interest.

Child or youth becomes a permanent and legal member of a family with all the legal rights of a birth child.

Adoption is a lifelong legal relationship that cannot be modified in court.
{% endDefinition %}

{% Definition "Legal Status" %}
Parental rights are relinquished or terminated unless it is a customary adoption established through Tribal court.
{% endDefinition %}

{% Definition "Legal Custody & Caregiver Responsibility After Permanent Plan Achieved" %}
Upon entry of adoption decree, the child or youth becomes the legal child or youth of the adoptive parents. The adoptive parents have all care, custody and legal rights to make decisions on the child's or youth's behalf. The child or youth has inheritance rights.

Title IVE adoption assistance can follow the youth to a subsequent adoption.
{% endDefinition %}

{%  Definition "Birth / Adoptive Parent Rights / Responsibility" %}
Adoptive parents assume full parental rights. Birth parents have no parental rights after termination of parental rights(TPR), unless a customary adoption established through Tribal court.

Birth and adoptive parent may have ongoing contact under an Open Adoption Agreement.
{% endDefinition %}

{%  Definition "Financial Services Available / Monthly Subsidy" %}
By applying for assistance through the adoption support program, adoptive parents may be eligible for finalization costs including legal fees. Families also may be eligible for a monthly cash reimbursement.
{% endDefinition %}

{%  Definition "Medical" %}
Medical and dental coverage for the child or youth is provided as specified in the adoption support agreement.

Pre-Authorized Counseling can be available and includes individual, family or adoptive parent counseling.

Specific contracted Combined In-Home services are also available to adoptive families.
{% endDefinition %}

{%  Definition "Educational Services" %}
Youth eligibility for post-high school grants and scholarships is program specific.

For college financial aid options visit a financial aid office at a local college or go to: https://studentaid.gov/h/apply-for-aid

Youth adopted after age 13 are eligible to complete FAFSA forms as an independent individual.
{% endDefinition %}

{%  Definition "Services Post 18 Years" %}
Adoption support benefits will automatically stop on the youth's 18th birthday, unless they meet eligibility requirements and the parents have provided documentation of the youth's continuation in high school prior to the 18th birthday.

If adopted after the age of 16, youth may be eligible to receive support up to age 21 through the Extended Adoption Support Program if the parents are providing financial support and the youth meets one of the following criteria:

1. Enrolled in high school or high school equivalency program.

2. Enrolled, has applied for, or can show intent to timely enroll in a post-secondary academic or vocational program.

3. Participating in a program to promote or remove barriers employment, including part-time employment.
{% endDefinition %}
</dl>

